The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                          Tuesday , November 10 , 2009                                                                                                                                                                                                                
	New Delhi: Former all-rounder and a member of the 1983 Cup winning squad, Mohinder Amaranth, was Monday honoured by the Board with the CK Nayudu Lifetime Achievement Award for the year 2008-09. Amarnath will receive the award, which comprises a trophy and a cheque for Rs 15 lakh, at the BCCI awards ceremony.        
	 Calcutta: Former India captain Mithali Raj improved her ranking by two spots to head the batters list and successor Jhulan Goswami was No.2 among the bowlers in the ICCs ODI womens rankings released Monday.         
	Wellington: New Zealander Eric Tindill became the worlds longest-living Test cricketer when he turned 98 years, 325 days, surpassing the record of Englands Francis MacKinnon who died in 1947.      
	Bopanna in  
	New Delhi: Rohan Bopanna beat second seed Louk Sorensen 4-6, 7-6(7-2), 6-3 to book a berth in the singles event of the ATP Challenger tournament in Aachen, Germany. Bopanna and his Pakistani partner Aisam-ul-Haq Qureshi are seeded second in the doubles event.      
	 Munich: Germany defender Philipp Lahm has apologised to Bayern Munich for his criticism of the management in a newspaper interview, an act for which he has already been fined by the club.        
	 Bad Wiessee (Germany): Former world junior champion Abhijeet Gupta finished joint leader after drawing his final round game in the International Open chess tournament here. He stands to gain important rating points in the meet that will take him to the coveted 2600 ELO rating mark.      
	London: World and Olympic champions Usain Bolt and Kenenisa Bekele were among five contenders shortlisted for the male Athlete of the Year award on Monday. Also on the shortlist are American sprinter Tyson Gay, Australian pole vaulter Steve Hooker and Norway rsquo;s javelin thrower Andreas Thorkildsen.      
	Guangzhou: The IOA chief Suresh Kalmadi was Monday re-elected unopposed as the president of the Asian Athletics Association (AAA) for his third consecutive four-year term.                                                                                                                                                                       
